Straw-man:

``` example
{
  "http://example.com": {
    "tls-ports": [443]
  },
  "http://www.example.com:81": {
    "tls-ports": [],
    "tls-commit": 86400
  }
  "http:/other.example.com": {
    "tis-ports": [443,8080],
    "tls-commit": 3600
  }
}
```

Thoughts?

Not sure we closed the original issue here - confirm?

I think we need:

```
{
  "http://example.com": {
    "tls-ports": [443]
  },
  "http://www.example.com:81": {
    "tls-ports": [],
    "tls-commit": true
  }
  "http:/other.example.com": {
    "tis-ports": [443,8080],
    "tls-commit": true
  }
}
```

With some sort of lifetime mechanism. That could be a `lifetime` member, or it could be HTTP caching freshness lifetime.

If we have a `lifetime` member, I think we have to either a) require it on EVERY origin, or b) fall back to HTTP caching freshness lifetime.

I know my preference. @martinthomson?

@bryancall 

> If a request is made on a stream with the header `:authority: www.yahoo.com`, then only the resources in the cache digest would be from the hostname www.yahoo.com. Is this understanding correct?

Yes. That is what the current draft states (or tries to state).

@bryancall - the scope is the origin, which is a bit more than the `:authority` -- it's the tuple of `(scheme, hostname, port)`.

@tombergan and @bryancall - I think that tying cache digest to cookie scopes would be a very hard sell. All new mechanisms in the Web use origins as a default administrative boundary, and doing anything scoped bigger than that is going to invite a lot of attention and controversy.

Having said that, there's nothing that stops a client from sending multiple cache digests on a connection, one for each origin that the connection is authoritative for. If this needs to be clarified in the draft we can certainly do that.

@martinthomson's feelings are well-known, as are (probably) mine.

It's a pity you can't subscribe to a label, rather than just a whole repo. I do agree that as this repo gets more active, it becomes more difficult for casual or selective participation. 

@mcmanus any thoughts?

Parallel thread: https://lists.w3.org/Archives/Public/ietf-http-wg/2016JulSep/thread.html#msg436

@rousskov I appreciate where you're coming from, but (personally, at least) I think that paints an overly black and white prognosis. I think we _could_ make reasonable progress here with a restricted set + browsers enforcement.

@kazuho @mnot I can't shake the feeling that restricting to integer values will come back to bite us, but if you think otherwise.. _shrug_, we can give it a shot.

> FWIW, another plausible thing to do would be to require conformance to the I-JSON profile (see https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc7493).

@reschke that's effectively what we proposed above.. ECMA-262 and I-JSON dictate same rules for number encoding?

