- https://lists.w3.org/Archives/Public/ietf-http-wg/2016OctDec/0099.html
- https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-kamp-httpbis-structure/

@reschke yes, I think that looks reasonable. 

> Furthermore, ordering of object members is not significant and can not be relied upon.

Paging @clelland @esprehn for sanity check..

@yoavweiss 
In addition to my previous comments, I think you cannot _expand_ an existing Cuckoo Filter. 

In other words, every time the number of resources that need to be tracked doubles (or halves), you would need to reconstruct a new Cuckoo Filter (of the adjusted size) by iterating through the cache entries. I do not think that is something you would like to do.

So, in the current iteration of structured headers, I think this question applies to both Dictionaries and Parameterised Labels.

Currently, Dictionaries forbid repeating members ("If dictionary already contains this_key, raise an error."). Similar language is in the parsing algorithm for parameterised labels. 

If that remains, it would be good to reinforce this in requirements (rather than just leaving it in the algorithms) for Dictionaries; Parameterised Labels already does that.

**If** Alt-Svc were defined as a structured header, I think QUIC's use case could be shoe-horned in; e.g.,

    Alt-Svc: hq=":49288";quic="1,51303334"

That's not pretty, of course, but I question how common this particular scenario is (most headers that need to be ordered can just use a list).

For @jyasskin's use case, something similar can happen (whitespace is a natural choice for delimiting URLs); e.g.,

    Signature: sig2;
      sig=*MEQCIGjZRqTRf9iKNkGFyzRMTFgwf/BrY2ZNIP/dykhUV0aYAiBTXg+8wujoT4n/W+cNgb7pGqQvIUGYZ8u8HZJ5YH26Qg;
      validityUrl="https://example.com/resource.validity https://fallback.example.net/foo";
      certUrl="https://example.com/certs https://and.another.example.org/bar";
      certSha256=*kQAA8u33cZRTy7RHMO4+dv57baZL48SYA2PqmYvPPbg;
      date=1511301183; expires=1511905983

If we allowed multiple instances of Dictionary (and Parameterised Label) keys, I'm concerned that it would be significantly more difficult to map structured headers into common data structures, and therefore would increase the friction against the introduction of generic parsing and serialisation tools for them -- as well as complicate their use. Remembering that the goal for SH is **not** to be able to express every conceivable header, but to get the 80% of "cream", I think this is a good tradeoff.

@estark37: Implementation-wise, it's not much work to accept a comma-delimited list instead of semicolons. However, since this is so similar to CSP/HPKP/HSTS, I'd _prefer_ it to have a similar structure of semicolon delineation, particularly since the reporting mechanism looks so much like CSP. It feels like it'd be weird to see the different delimiters side-by-side:

```
    add_header	           Strict-Transport-Security "max-age=31536000; includeSubDomains; preload";
    add_header             Content-Security-Policy "default-src 'self'; script-src 'unsafe-eval' 'unsafe-inline' 'self' ... ; img-src data: 'self'; ... ";
    add_header             Expect-CT "enforce, max-age=1";
```

