So to summarise, I think the proposal is:

* Allow parameters on Item
* Allow parameters on inner-list

This removes the need to make parameters specific to Dictionaries and lists, and effectively allows parameters "everywhere". This is probably a very good story for extensibility, if we document it right.

The only downside that I see is that implementations will no longer map "simple" types (e.g., integers, strings) to their analogies in-language; it'll all need to be objects, to accommodate parameters.

I think that's acceptable -- especially given the token/string schism -- but wanted to make sure everyone understood this. 

For the test suite, it means that the JSON representation of an item will probably be something like:

~~~ json
{
  "value": 12335,
  "parameters": {
    "foo": 456.78
}
~~~

and with an inner-list:

~~~ json
{
  "value": [
    {
      "value": "a",
      "parameters": {
        "foo": true
      }
    },
    {
      "value": "b"
    }
  ],
  "parameters": {
    "foo": "bar"
  }
}
~~~

This is _verbose_, but fairly straightforward. And of course APIs can make this a lot easier with various methods (e.g., `getParameters` and the like).

What do people think? This is not a small change, so I'm likely to do it in an isolated draft version. There aren't *that* many implementations yet, so if we're going to do this, now is the time.

This was already discussed; see #790. 

